Next, individual example spheroids were selected to demonstrate the nuances of the invasion metrics. We generated polar plots depicting invasion past the boundary for the selected spheroids and calculated their quantitative metrics (Fig. 2). As demonstrated by comparing polar plots of individual NHF and SMC spheroids (Fig. 2A,B), the area change is not necessarily correlated with distance. Panel B shows a spheroid that does not invade as far as the spheroid in Panel A, resulting in a lower distance, but the invasion distribution is denser, resulting in a higher area change. Due to these differences in invasion density and distance, these spheroids have a nearly equal value (~ 0.001 mm4) for the radial area moment of inertia demonstrating that the moment metric is less influenced by invasion distribution differences than the area change and distance metrics alone.Fig. 2
